Here they are:,Lesson 1:,The proposed lesson is applicable in case of optical instruments based on holographic grating spectrometers where straylight is a key requirement.The proposed lesson is to incorporate the main parameters of the holographic setup during the definition of the optical design in order to have gratings that can be manufactured with holographic setup that is as simple as possible (virtually 2 point sources without collimating optics).,Lesson 2:,Testing conditions and aspects to take care of, do's and dont's, outliers and materials to avoid, radiation hard designs vs standard product. The RADGLASS project and approach in establishing a database of optical materials spectral transmittance properties versus radiation dose has been extremely valuable. This database is publically available on request. Access is frequently requested by European space industry, research institutes and internationally. The database should be actively maintained and kept up to date with new results.,Lesson 3:,There must be a really good reason not to build a cryogenic instrument from metal (i.e. Aluminium). Working with ceramic materials, such as SiC, is much more costly and difficult. Please wait a moment :),Here is the only lesson I have on 'Buzz Aldrin':,Buzz Aldrin (/ldrn/; born Edwin Eugene Aldrin Jr.; January 20, 1930) is an American former astronaut, engineer and fighter pilot. He made three spacewalks as pilot of the 1966 Gemini 12 mission. As the Lunar Module Eagle pilot on the 1969 Apollo 11 mission, he and mission commander Neil Armstrong were the first two people to land on the Moon. Born in Glen Ridge, New Jersey, Aldrin graduated third in the class of 1951 from the United States Military Academy at West Point, with a degree in mechanical engineering. He was commissioned into the United States Air Force, and served as a jet fighter pilot during the Korean War. He flew 66 combat missions and shot down two MiG-15 aircraft. After earning a Doctor of Science degree in astronautics from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Aldrin was selected as a member of NASA's Astronaut Group 3, making him the first astronaut with a doctoral degree. His doctoral thesis, Line-of-Sight Guidance Techniques for Manned Orbital Rendezvous, earned him the nickname Dr. Rendezvous" from fellow astronauts. His first space flight was in 1966 on Gemini 12 during which he spent over five hours on extravehicular activity. Three years later
column3: Aldrin set foot on the Moon at 03:15:16 on July 21
column5: nineteen minutes after Armstrong first touched the surface
column6: while command module pilot Michael Collins remained in lunar orbit. A Presbyterian elder
column7: Aldrin became the first person to hold a religious ceremony on the Moon when he privately took communion. Apollo 11 effectively proved U.S. victory in the Space Race by fulfilling a national goal proposed in 1961 by President John F. Kennedy "of landing a man on the Moon and returning him safely to the Earth" before the end of the decade. After leaving NASA in 1971
column8: Aldrin became Commandant of the U.S. Air Force Test Pilot School. He retired from the Air Force in 1972
column9: after 21 years of service. His autobiographies Return to Earth (1973) and Magnificent Desolation (2009) recount his struggles with clinical depression and alcoholism in the years after leaving NASA. Aldrin continues to advocate for space exploration
column10: particularly a human mission to Mars
column12: a special spacecraft trajectory that makes travel to Mars more efficient in terms of time and propellant. He has been accorded numerous honors
column13: including the Presidential Medal of Freedom in 1969.
